Referral for legal assistance does not reflect any opinion on the merits of a litigant’s case (see 
UCPR r 7.33(4)
). But a court should ordinarily be reluctant to order referrals where the claim appears to be without merit: Phu v NSW Dept of Education and Training [2011] NSWCA 119;  BC201103239 ; Hetherington-Gregory v All Vehicle Services (No 2) [2012] NSWCA 257;  BC201206337 . That general proposition is subject to the qualification that appropriate early legal advice may avoid unnecessary and futile litigation: Dafaalla v Concord Repatriation General Hospital [2007] NSWSC 602;  BC200704630 at [5], [9]  per Brereton J (certificate granted for limited purposes of advice and if the claim is arguable for drafting and settling an amended statement of claim). See also Lindsay v Health Care Complaints Commission (No 2) [2009] NSWCA 150;  BC200905075  (appellant referred to Registrar for referral to a barrister on pro bono panel — referral limited to assistance in preparing specified documents and settling affidavits); Bobolas v Waverley Council [2011] NSWCA 242;  BC201106274  (request for pro-bono representation granted — not likely to obtain legal assistance outside the scheme — “exorbitant” delay by Legal Aid Review Committee in considering review application); Kelly v Mosman Municipal Council (2010) 178 LGERA 136; [2010] NSWCA 370;  BC201009839  (referral to give advice relating to grounds of appeal and the prosecution of the appeal); Rouvinetis v Knoll [2012] NSWCA 125;  BC201202856  (referral refused at first instance because judge not satisfied that the plaintiff would take the advice of the person appointed and the appointment would be a futility — single judge of appeal subsequently satisfied that referral should be made to obtain legal assistance for appeal — in the interests of the administration of justice especially given the nature and complexity of the proceedings); Carnemolla v Adelaide Bank Ltd [2012] NSWCA 152;  BC201203553  (referral allowed — legal aid refused, complex proceedings, limited means — initial referral limited, further assistance dependent on outcome of initial referral).
